{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_echidna_ver01/data/sn82015425/00529040660/1949062601/0498.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE SIX\nBartha Perry Memorial Thrift\nClub Observes Ist Anniversary\nOn laht Sunday the Bertha Perry\nMemorial Thrift Club for the Col\nored Blind held ite first anniversary\nnt the Mount Sinai Baptist church\nWith over 600 persons on hand to\nwe a program presided over entire\nly by blind. The Thrift Club is a\nand saving., association of At\nlanta colored blind.\nThe Rev. Homer L. Smith deliver\ned the anniversary sermon. Rev.\nSmith commended the organ latten\n<>n it* foresight and the excellent\npi<>gram that they have. He stated\nthat because of such programs as\nthese the bbqd are not. as helpless\nin the era as they were in former\nyears He also praised the Metro\npolitan Atlanta Association for the\ntailored Blind of the Butler Street\nYMCA for its part In pushing the\nb mil program to the forefront. The\nmusic was under the direction of\nAlbert J Lewis and the chorus of the\nMAACB sang \"Christ is All\" apd\nUniversity Thespians\nIn Brilliant Performance\nBY LERONE BENNETT, JR.\nNorman Krasna\u2019s \"Dear Ruth,\"\nsuperbly performed by a sterling\n<ast of the Atlanta University Sum\nmer Theatre, played in time-mel\nlowed Howe Hall on Spelman\u2019s cam\npus Thursday Friday, and Saturday\nnights before standing-room crowds\nBaldwin W burroughs, brilliant\nand talented young actor, critic and\ndirector, paced the young thespians\nthrough a poluhed performance.\nFred Holmes, newcomer to the\nSummer Theatre (although well\nknown in the University Players\n\"Faihidn\" and others;! stcl? the\nhearts of the shirt-sleeved audience\nalong with the equally-talented and\nequally brilliant Ella Mae Gaines,\nwho turned in a convincing interpre\ntation of Ruth Wilkins, the older,\nmore mature daughter of Judge and\nMrs Harry Wilkins, acted with a\ngreat deal of finesse by Lincoln\nBlakenev and Georgia Allen\nHolmes was cast as Lieutenant\nWilliam Seawright, a lonely soldier\nwho. after receiving love letters\nfrom an anonymous young lady, re\nturn* home to claim this young lady\na-, his own. The plot spun around\nSen wright's court-ship of Ruth tEha\nMac Gainesr who supposedly wrote\nthe letters although the\nletters were written by Ruth\u2019s young\npatriotic and impulsive young sister.\nMiriam, who was played by chann\nmg Jane Hunter. Holmes\u2019 accent a\nIn Boyer, suave mannerisms and\nDID roO\ntoil A\nS \\_\nBILL?\nMryh. H't on Moor\u2014ln your cle,*\u00ab\nnvnry pair of worn \u00abSoe\u00ab you ran\nSort in Mrv\u00aba will r\u00abpo\u00bb yeu \u00ab\u00abv\u00abrol <fol.\n\u2022rn tn w\u00ab\u00abw of today .Hor prk\u00ab<\nC<k up Pint monay Sona m yaw W\n\u2019Sort \u00abn 4 let w mot* M\u00bbm\n\u2014\u00ab\u00abMM\u00ab raw.\nWe call for\nand deliver\nWhitehead Shoe\nRebuilders\n651 FAIR ST., 5 W.\nWA. 6689\nANNOUNCEMENT\nooOoo\nR W. WOODWARD, Well Known A\u00bblon\u00bbo Barber, Now Op\nerating His Own Shop al 160 Elm St., S. W, announces his\nemploying three expert barbers to assist him in serving his\ncustomers. The assisting barbers are: Messrs. Glenn Ervin\nBell, William M. Sims, Jr., and Arthur lee Nails.\nooOoo\nCustomers desiring appointments for work may call the\nSHOP\u2014ALPINE 9374; RESIDENCE-LAMAR 1514\nATLANTA'S GREATEST RECORD SALE\nt. r w 3\nPOPUIAR SIUES, BOOGIE. JAZZ AND SPIRITUAIS\nWe |wve LOST OUR LEASE As A Retull It Is Necessary to\nCLOSE OUT OUR ENTIRE STOCK\nABSOLUTELY ALL RECORDS\n49c\nMANY OF tHESt RECORDS FORMAU Y SOID FOR AS MUCH AS Vis\nOyr loss Is Your Gain\nEDGEWOOD MUSIC SHOP\n201 EDGEWOOD AVENUE, S I\nDown on My Knees. O C Stan\nfield gave a brief history of the\nclub Mrs. Humphrey Moore sang\nsolo \u201cLord Jesus Remarks were\nnad< by John J Thornton and\nMrs. Mary Mullins, acting presi\ndent of the group. P J Woods,\nvducalional Dteeetor of the MAACB\npresented to the group persons who\ni lad worked with the blind program.\nMrs. Menelik Jackson, chairman\n>f the Advisory Committee of the\nMAACB and Mrs Nella Curgil of\nhe finance committee also gave re\nnarks and praised the work of the\nJub The Bertha Perry Memorial\nThrift Club for the blind is open\nboth blind and sighted persons\nvho are interested in the work of\nhe blind Miss C B. Enzer of the\nu\u00abff of the MAACB presided over\n1 he meting Miss Savannah Ivory,\nI irector of the Pittsburgh Extension\nepresented the \u201cY\" al the obser\nance.\ntrue-to-life gestures endeared him\nto the receptive audience.\nMiss Qaines, playing opposite Hol\nmes, adding her loveliness to a fine\nacting ability, turned in a truly\ngrand performance. Behind an old\nbriar pipe and patches of gray hair,\nLincoln Blakeney, as Judge Wilkins,\nkept the spectators in gales of laugh\nter with his well-timed and witty\nremarks. Georgia Allen, cast as his\nwife, a charming and petulant\nmothei of two girls Interpreted pro\nfessionally a difficult role\nIn a different vein. J Preston\nCochrane, as the distraught Albert\nKummer, hopelessly in love with\nRuth, whom he is destined to lose\nto the more romantic Lt Seawright\nwas quite convincing. His gesticula\ntions and well-turned barbs evoked\nloads of laughter from the audience.\nIn the lesser roles, but vieing for\nacting honors were Mary Ella\nSmith, as the querulous maid; Rasa\nlie Slack, as the patient and under\nstanding sister of Lt Seawright;\nWalter Clements, as Sgt. Chuck\nVincent, the Lieutenant\u2019s pal; and\nHarold Pride, as Harold Klobbcr\nmeyer. a second deluded soldier who\npops up in the last, ad\nFrom the moment the curtains\nparted with scattered applause for\nthe stage setting, until the final\ncurtain closed, the audience was\nheld by the catching comedy, the\nswiftly moving action, and the su\nperb acting of an inspired cast.\nD Rene Todd served as techni\ncian to Mr Burroughs Mr Todd\nis to direct, the next plav \"Noah\",\nwhich will lie presented on July 7.\n8 and 9\nMembers of the production staff,\nwhose work in the auxiliary units\nmade the play possible, were: Mamie\nThompson, stage manager; Sam\nHarris and Harlow Mosley, lighting;\nBertram Sears, Louie Robinson, Dor\nsey Williams, James Montgomery.\nCharles Releford, Willard Hart,\nbuilding: Alvin Mitchell, Walter\ni Clement*, painting; Delores Posey,\ncostumes: Ernel Combs. Muriel\nCorrin. Elizabeth Reed, properties;\nand McClure P McCootnbs. busi\nnesg manager\nNew 14,000 ton vessel planned un\nder United States .subsidy\nNational Archives to use micro\nfilm instead of new building\nH. M. Jackson Guest\nSpeaker At St. Cecelia\nVesper Services Today\nHubert M Jackson. manager j\nJohn Hope-University Homes and\nwell-known civic leader, will, be\nguest speaker at ttje June Vesper\nServices of the St. Cecelia Child-\nten's Choir, at sp. m.. todav at\nSt Paul AME Church. Rev H I\nBearden, pastor\nMr Jackson, a\nnative of New\n4 York City, holds\n|JEIhI baccalaureate de\n^^^Birees from Lin\n^^Mcoln University.\nthe Atlanta\n\u25a0\u25a0university School\nif Social Work\n\u25a0^H ind has done ad\n\u25a0HH anced work in\nhousing at Neu\n^\u2019\u25a0York University.\nMusical features\n>n today\u2019s pro-\ngram will include\nH. M. JACKSON two piano duetts\nand an instrumental trio. Teaming\nup on tme piano will be Miss M.\nRobinson and Clarence Robinson\nfor a selection, then Miss Essie\nJewell and Beverly Leverett will\nplay \"Quivivi\" by Ganz Blending\ninstrumental tones tn the trio will\nbe Mis Juanita Collier, violin; Miss\nBernice Byron, \u2019cello; and Miss\nLeatrice Traylor, piano.\nAmong the choral numbers to be\nlendered by the well-trained St.\nCecelia Children's Choir are: \u201cGo\nDown Moses,\" \u201cDrink To Me Only\nWith Thine Eyes,\u201d and \u201cGod of Our\nFathers Known of Old.\" Choirmas\nter Earl A. Starling will conduct the\nchoir, with Miss Leatrice Traylor,\naccompanist.\nHAPEVILLE, GA.\nj Of interest to the community was\na program sponsored by the P. T\nA., of the school honoring the\nFaculty also Mr. Charles Bryant, a\nMorehouse graduate. Miss Dorothy\nBarnett presided at the piano with\nthe congregation .singing America.\ni Prayer by Rev. C. L. Burney. Read\nIngs by Mrs. Lillie Bell Bozeman\nand Little Misses .Clementine and\nGloria Jean Burney. Solo by Miss\nJeanie Bryant. Instrumental solos\nby Misses Dorthy Barnett, Leatrice\nTraylor and Little Adaira Early.\nSpeeches by Mrs. Estella Freeman\nof East Point and Mrs, L. M. Ward\nington, principal of Hunter Hill\nSchool.\nWe wish to thank the following\nteachers for their splendid work of\n1948-49; Miss R L. Goss, Mrs. F\nW. Wilson, Mrs. Ruby Hurd and\nMrs. Gilbert. Folowing the program\nwas a reception for the honored\nguests and well wishers in the\n(school auditorium. Mrs. R. M. Cof\nfee is president\nReligious Movies To\nBe Shown Wednesday\nAnd Thursday Nights\nThere will be shown two religion^\npictures \u201cThe Prodical Son\" and\n\u201cNo Greater Power\u201d at. the McDay\nFuncraf Home, Thursday, June 30\nat 8 p. in.\nWednesday night, June 29 these\npictures will also be shown at 843\nMason Turner Avenue at 8 p. m.\nAdults 25c. children 15c.\nDEATHS\nSASSENE. Mrs, Cora, of 667 Del\nbridge St, passed at her residence\nJune 23\nDAVtS. Mr John passed June 23,\nat his residence Jackson, Ga.\nCENTER. Mrs. Ella, 538 Strong\nSt.. N W., died at the residence\nJune 24\nWOOLFOLK. Mrs. Sarah, of 580\nDelbridge St., N W passed June\n24\nCRAWFORD. Mr Henry, of 318\nRaspberry Ailey died June 23.\nLEWIS, Mr Gilmore, of Social\nCircle. Ga., passed May 23.\nGETER. Mrs Elnora, of 924 Sims\nSt.. 8. W died at. the residence\nJune 24.\nKNIGHT. Mr Charlie passed at\nIbe residence June 24\nRecord 3,510,000 received publlt\naid in fiscal year\nExpectant fathers get advice in\nrevised Government book.\nAtom bomb seen as not enough\nfor defense of West Europe.\nU. S to back international fairs\nas spur to imports.\nATLANTA DAILY WORUJ. ATLANTA. GEORGIA\nATLANTANS INVITED TO\nTECH STUDENTS MODELS\nA model of a proposed redevelop\nment project of Atlanta\u2019s old fourth\nward area, principally the section\nknown as \u201cdarktown,\" will be ex\nhibited this week in the Urban\nLeague Offices m the Herndon\nBuilding.\nDesigned by senior engineering\nstudents at The Georgia School of\nTechnology, the model shows what\ncould and should be done to make\na beautiful, livable, modern com\nmunity out of what the students\ncall \u201cthe black heart of Atlanta\nIn the scale model layout of the\nredevelopment, of the area, the stu\noents have utilized the latest\nthinking and methods in communi\nty planning. They have not only\nprovided houses for residential pur\nposes. but also buildings tor schools,\nhospitals, clinics, churches, recrea\ntional centers, and community shops\nParks, green areas, and other out-\nJackson Tells Of Visit,\nSnub At Dragon *s Office\nBY MARION E. JACKSON\nJoseph M. Goldwaser, the Cleve\nland, Ohio department store tycoon\nwas in a chatty mood as we (Ro\nbert Johnson and I' sat in the re\nception room of Grand Dragon\nSamuel Green Friday. We asked:\n\"Are you officially representing the\nNational Association for the Ad\nvancement of Colored People?\" The\nspotlight enjoying Goldwasser\nanswered \"No. I am in Georgia on\non my own.\"\nWe chimed in \u201cWhen did you ar\nrive in Atlanta? \"The Ben Blue\nlooking Goldwasser answered \"Yes\nterday, and I have been going\nevery since I have been here.\"\n\u201cWhat is the purpose of your\nvisit?\u201d we asked.\nGoldwasser answered \"I have in\nformation of vital importance re\ngarding Jews, Catholics and Ne\ngroes.\u201d\n\u201cWhat is the nature of this infor\nmation?\u201d We queried \u201cWe would\nlike to have an inkling since it is of\nsuch importance you made a spe\ncial trip to Atlanta.\u201d\nThe answer came, \"1 can\u2019t tell\nyou now, but after my interview I\nam going to give each of you a co\npy of my statement. However, I\ndon't think lam going to have\nenough tn go around. I only have 8\ncopies.\"\n\u201cBy the way. where are you\nfellows from?\u201d he asked. I answer\ned \"The Atlanta Daily World.\"\nGoldwasser \u2018puzzled \u2018\u201cls it a\nweeklv like the Courier.\u2019 \"No.\" Ro\nbert E. Johnson my accompanying\nscribe answered. \"It is a daily.\"\n\"A daily?\" Goldwasser stated \"It\nis the first Negro daily I ever heard\nof but seems like I have heard of\nit somewhere.'\nI butted in. \"I think I gave you\nI several copies down in Lyons, Ga.\"\nGoldwasser intoned \"Oh, yes\nwere you there. Bov they certainly\nhustled me out of there. I never did\nj get a chance to give my information\non the case.\" Meanwhile, more\nnewspaper reporters were arriving.\nGoldwasser halted one. \"Say fel\nlow. you know' you misquoted me.\u201d\nThe two went into a detailed state\nment of the item involved. The re\nporter brought it. to an end with \"I\ni didn't misquote you. I am afraid\nthe felow that told you did.\u201d\nThe Grand Dragon's secretary\nthen appeared Would the reporters\npleare put their names on the sheet\nof paper? All of the newsmen com\nlied.\nThe Atlanta Daily World report\ners were ignored. Meanwhile, more\nreporters were arriving. The great\nmoment was at hand Goldwasser\nwas noticeably nervous\nThe Grand Dragon then appear\n|Pd in the doorway of his office. He\ni appeared plainly irked at. the re-\nSTOP! LOOK! READ!\nFor Your Special\nSUMMER LUNCHES\nHAWK'S DINETTE, 306 Auburn Ave.\nLAMAR 0777\nSpecials Priced To Suit Every One\nCRISP LETTUCE AND TOMATO SANDWICH 15c\nTOASTED AMERICAN CHEESE SANDWICH 2(k\nBACON AND EGG SANDWICH 25c\nSOUR KRAUT WITH FRANKS RYF BRFAD TIA\nOR LEMONADE 40c\nSLICED COLD CHICKEN SANDWICH POTATO CHIPS\nLEMONADE 45c\nTOASTED CLUB SANDWICH WITH DRINK 45c\nBAKED SPICED HAM WITH POTATO SALAD,\nPICKLE DRINK 50c\nHOT ROAST SIRLOIN OF BEEF SANDWICH WITH\nSNOWFLAKE POTATOES DRINK 50c\nFRESH SHRIMP SALAb WITH SALTINES\nTEA OR LEMONADE 60c\nHAWK S SPECIAL COLD PLATE 40<\nREGULAR DINNERS\nSERVED DAILY\nAA GRADE T-BONE STEAKS JUMBO SHRIMPS FRIED\nSHRIMPS FRIED CHICKEN ASSORTED ICE CREAM\nHOMI BAKED PIES SOFT DRINKS MILK JUICES\nSPECIAL NOTICE\nPICNIC BOXES PREPARED ON DAY'S NOTICE\nPrivate Dining Room Service For Small Partie*\nSee\"H AWK'S\"For\nTHE BEST IN\nFOOD AND PRICES\ndoor recreational areas, now pr dl\ntically non-existant. are provided\nShould some patron saint of the t\npoor man wave a magic wand and\nmake passible the building of the\nhuge project, the Tech students es\ntimate that it would cost about\n$72,060,000.\nThe area covered by the project\ni is bounded by Courtland and Pied\nmont North Ave, the Southern R\nR Beltline, and Edgewood Avenue\nAvailable statistics show that crime,\ndisease, poverty, and land-owners\ngreed, are rampant in the section,\nclassified as one of the major slum\nareas of the city.\nUrban League officials are ex\ntending *n invitation to the public\nto see the scale model of the Tech\nstudents\u2019 ambitious idea It will be\non display, beginning tomorrow\nmorning from 9 a. m to 5 p. m\norters present. Goldwasser and\nGreen sparred. The Dragon stated\nhe hadn\u2019t agreed to have reorters\npresent for the interview. Goldwas\nser insisted he did. Green then\nagreed.\nRobert Johnson and I started for\nthe office where the interview was\nto be held along with other repor\nters. The Grand Dragon halted us\nwith \u201cI don\u2019t allow Negroes in my\nreception room and you can\u2019t stay.\u201d\nI suggested holding the interview\njin the hall. Reporters crowded\naround us. We gave our names and\nsuggested that one of the reporters\nask our lead question for us.\nI It. was \u201cArc American Indians\nqualified for membership in the Ku\njKlux Klan?\u201d We wanted to Know\nsince the KKK poses as an Ameri-\ni can organization primarily mteres'\ned in preserving \"our American way\nof life.\u201d We were curious to know\nif some real Americans could be\ninitiated into the ritualistic society\nGoldwaser was immediately apo\nlogetic to Dr. Green's snubbing us\n\"Wait,\u2019 he said \u201cI will give you fel\nlows an interview later.\u201d He didn\u2019t\nintercede with the Grand Dragon\non our behalf. We saw the shadows\nof the Grand Dragon and Goldwas-\nIsec and the reporters through opa\nque door. We didn\u2019t wait.\nGoldwasser\u2019s intervention in the\nlynch-slaying of Robert E. Mallard\nin Lyons, Ga., has never truly been\nexplained. His appearance at. th*\ntrial acompanying Mrs. Amy James\nMalard was controversial and the\ni evidence be was supposed to have\nhearing on the case has never been\nrevealed. Goldwasser came to At\nlanta to interview the Grand Dra\ngon, He still has to explain his mo\ntives.\nRace Relations Institute\nAt Fisk U. June 27-July 9\nNASHVILLE, Tenn. Forty lect\nurers and consultants will highlight\nthe discussom on civil and human\nrights at the Sixth Institute of\nRace Relations of the American\nMissionary Association at Fisk Uni\nversity. June 27-July 9. Leading au\nthorities in human rights in this\ncountry and Great Britian, the\nspeakers represent the professional\nand scientific fields of sociology,\nlaw, psychiatry, education, religion,\nlabor, and business. A student body\nof 125 members is expected, com\ning from about 33 states and Cana\nda.\nThe Institute began in 1944. dur\ning the period of high wartime ra\ncial tension, as a laboratory for\nlln Memoriam\nIN SAD BUT loving memory of\netu wife and mother. Ardeller D\nRender, who departed this hfe one\nyear ago, June 25. 1948.\nHow hard it was to say goodbye\nOn that lonely sad day.\nBut we know that God loves\nyou most\nWhen he calls you away.\nSadly missed\nHomer Render, husband,\nFreddie Render,\nRase Kate Rendei.\nAnnie Lee Johnson,\nMinnie Lee Troutman and\nFriends\nIn Memoriam\nIN SAD BUT LOVING MEMORY\nof our dear son and brother. Mr.\nEugene Brumfield, who departed\nthis life four years ago, June 29.\n1945.\n\u201cDeath is a heartache\nNo one can heal.\nLove is a treasure\nNo one can steal.\u201d\nThe Brumfields and Family\nIn Memoriam\nIN LOVING MEMORY of our\nmother, sister and aunt, Mrs. Mi.-\nlie Ann Williams who passed June\n21, 1935.\n\u201cFrom this world of pain and\nsorrow\nTo a land of peace and rest\nGod took you there\nWhere won would find eternal\nrest.\u201d\nMrs. M. F. Williams\nMrs. M. D. Williams, daughters\nMrs. Mary Sams, sister\nMr. E. L. Matthews, nephew\nMiss Mary Matthews, niece\nIn Memoriam\nIN LOVING MEMORY of our\ndear one. Miss Ruby Gertrude Lane,\nwho passed away two years ago. to\nday, June 27, 1947.\n\u201cLife is -eal, life is earnest.\nAnd its grave is not its gold.\nDust thou art to dust rctumeth\nWas not spoken of the souL\u2019\nMrs. Annie Lane, mother,\nMrs. Belle Lane Howard, sister.\nMr. I. M. Lane,\nJasper M. Lane,\nHerman A. Lane and John O\nLane, brothers.\nNOT SO SAFE FOR THREE\nBUCKRUS, Ohio A party ar\nrknged by the people of this town tn\nhonor and \u201csafeguard\" local high\nschool graduates, following their an\nnual junior-senior banquet, was dis\nrupted when three youths, two of\nwhom were high school seniors,\nwere killed when their automobile\ncrashed into a moving freight train\non a fog-shrouded highway. Towns\nfolk had arranged a 2 a. tn break\nfast. at the country club, to keep the\nyoungsters under control \u2014and safe\n\u2014during lheir celebration of com\nmencement.\nLord Samuel says Irsael will pay\nArab refugees for land\ntraining community leaders to meet\nj local problems. This year's program\nwill focus upon the SOCIAL AND\nPOLITICAL IMPLICATIONS OF\nHUMAN RIGHTS, as these former\nlocal and national issues assume in\nternational significance in the cur\ni rent political scene.\nThe keynote address of the Insti\nj tute will be given by Dr. Charles S.\nJohnson, President of Fisk Universi\ntv and Director of the Institute, at.\n2:30 Monday afternoon June 27, in\nthe Social Science Building.\nMonday evening, in the Fisk\nChapel at 8:00 o'clock. Dr. Reginald\nBarrett. Cambridge University so\nciologist and visiting lecturer at\nFisk University, wi